WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.680
I'm Trevor Nutterwalf, a solution engineer at Posit.

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:15.500
And back in 2016, I failed my coworker, Sam.

00:00:15.500 --> 00:00:21.620
So imagine this, Sam, late from his commute, has 10 minutes to spare before an important

00:00:21.620 --> 00:00:23.200
executive meeting.

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:29.879
He comes racing in the office, fires up a shiny app to grab the latest report, and this

00:00:29.879 --> 00:00:30.879
happens.

00:00:30.879 --> 00:00:34.720
Oh, no, undefined column.

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:38.959
Sam quickly has to grab the report from yesterday and explain it well.

00:00:38.959 --> 00:00:40.919
The meeting did not go well.

00:00:40.919 --> 00:00:42.439
I failed my coworker.

00:00:42.439 --> 00:00:47.639
But let's look at why this happened.

00:00:47.639 --> 00:00:51.639
So Friday, I push a tiny fix to my app.

00:00:51.639 --> 00:00:57.759
I give it a few quick tests manually, and it's the end of the day, and so I forget to

00:00:57.759 --> 00:01:01.360
deploy it, but I figure I'll do it early on Monday.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:03.000
Monday rolls around.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:09.239
I deploy the app, thinking it's working, and then the fateful Tuesday happens.

00:01:09.239 --> 00:01:15.080
Sam has trouble getting the report, and it really hurts his performance.

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:19.199
But the good news is that was back in 2016.

00:01:19.199 --> 00:01:27.800
Let's look at an alternative reality if this happened in 2023 with better tooling.

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:35.360
So now I make my tiny fix, but this time I push it up to my GitHub repo, and my CICD

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:40.480
pipeline runs, does a test, and flags the error.

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:43.839
The shiny app doesn't look right.

00:01:43.839 --> 00:01:44.839
That's great.

00:01:44.839 --> 00:01:47.400
I can go back, and I can make the fix on Monday.

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:50.040
I get in a little early because I know the error occurred.

00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:52.120
I saw it on my email.

00:01:52.120 --> 00:01:53.800
I make the changes.

00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:55.720
I push it up to GitHub.

00:01:55.720 --> 00:01:58.440
My CICD pipeline runs.

00:01:58.440 --> 00:02:00.720
Tests succeed, and great.

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:04.559
It deploys the new version of my app to my server.

00:02:04.559 --> 00:02:11.059
Now Sam runs in, 10 minutes to spare, goes to the app, downloads the report.

00:02:11.059 --> 00:02:12.600
It comes out really fast.

00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:14.119
He can drink his coffee.

00:02:14.119 --> 00:02:15.320
He gets his caffeine hit.

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:16.320
He goes to his meeting.

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:17.880
He gets a huge promotion.

00:02:17.880 --> 00:02:19.399
He becomes my boss.

00:02:19.399 --> 00:02:26.199
He's the CEO of the company, and he buys a sports team someday, a wildly successful career.

00:02:26.199 --> 00:02:29.279
What a great alternative reality.

00:02:29.279 --> 00:02:32.479
We should all live in this world.

00:02:32.479 --> 00:02:37.020
So let's look at how I got here.

00:02:37.020 --> 00:02:39.960
So first, I set up a CICD pipeline.

00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:45.199
I use GitHub Actions, but there's other tools I'll talk about at the end.

00:02:45.199 --> 00:02:49.320
There's two main pieces, continuous integration, running the tests.

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:53.960
I used a package ShinyTest2, which allows you to record your screen.

00:02:53.960 --> 00:02:57.160
It's great and record how your app behaves.

00:02:57.160 --> 00:03:00.800
And then continuous delivery.

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:06.679
This deploys my app to Connect only if the CI steps are successful.

00:03:06.679 --> 00:03:11.160
So only at the end of the pipeline.

00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:15.059
It's a great time to be setting up CICD pipelines.

00:03:15.919 --> 00:03:20.380
And this is because in GitHub Actions, there's a lot of community pre-built steps.

00:03:20.380 --> 00:03:22.419
I've left some links here.

00:03:22.419 --> 00:03:28.779
RLib has a number of them useful for R users, and RStudio has some as well.

00:03:28.779 --> 00:03:33.460
And the purpose of this talk is not to go through code, but I did want to show just

00:03:33.460 --> 00:03:36.979
how easy it is to set up your own pipeline.

00:03:36.979 --> 00:03:42.539
You can compose different steps, kind of like packages, into your pipeline.

00:03:42.539 --> 00:03:51.380
So here, I set up R, I set up my RM environment, I run the test, and I publish to Connect.

00:03:51.380 --> 00:03:53.979
It's really this simple, and you can do it too.

00:03:53.979 --> 00:03:59.380
If there's one takeaway from this talk that I want you to have is to run out and set up

00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:00.380
your own pipeline.

00:04:00.380 --> 00:04:04.139
What do you have to lose?

00:04:04.139 --> 00:04:05.619
And there's a couple benefits.

00:04:05.619 --> 00:04:09.279
The main ones are deploying from Git repos.

00:04:09.279 --> 00:04:12.880
How nice is it that I can just commit to my repo and then trust my pipeline will do

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:13.880
the rest?

00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:18.959
It'll automate the tests, it'll only deploy the content after testing.

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:22.540
And the result of all this is my users will trust me.

00:04:22.540 --> 00:04:27.079
It's a good feeling to know that when you log on to an app, it's going to be successful.

00:04:27.079 --> 00:04:30.679
And that grows the user base within your company.

00:04:30.679 --> 00:04:31.679
And there's a lot of other tools.

00:04:31.679 --> 00:04:36.600
I talked about GitHub Actions, but if you're using any of these other ones, contact your

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:41.200
DevOps team or others on your team that have access and get started.

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:46.679
They all are fairly easy to use, and your team may already have some actions in the

00:04:46.679 --> 00:04:50.480
pipeline that you don't even know about.

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:53.279
I'll leave you with a few resources.

00:04:53.279 --> 00:04:57.279
You're always welcome to contact me and reach out with any questions.

00:04:57.279 --> 00:04:59.160
I'm happy to help.

00:04:59.160 --> 00:05:01.959
Get out there and make some awesome pipelines.

